law school, because I

00:13:19.440 --> 00:13:23.550
saw that this was a method that
would be pretty awesome for me.

00:13:23.550 --> 00:13:26.600
And I say to my
boss, Peter Connect,

00:13:26.600 --> 00:13:28.470
I'm just going to stay here.

00:13:28.470 --> 00:13:31.470
But I did happen to
notice way down the hall

00:13:31.470 --> 00:13:33.990
there was that vacant office.

00:13:33.990 --> 00:13:37.230
This office was
twice as big as his.

00:13:37.230 --> 00:13:41.100
But he didn't care, because
he started with Jack Warner

00:13:41.100 --> 00:13:42.480
like a zillion years ago.

00:13:42.480 --> 00:13:45.130
And so he just goes,
I'll get it for you.

00:13:45.130 --> 00:13:50.100
He gets me this giant office,
the size of this room.

00:13:50.100 --> 00:13:54.220
But really, with two
union secretaries there.

00:13:54.220 --> 00:13:57.390
So now, I have this
amazing, big office.

00:13:57.390 --> 00:14:01.050
And I can use this for
the Brian Grazer business,

00:14:01.050 --> 00:14:04.360
even though I'm working there
and still making my $5 an hour.

00:14:04.360 --> 00:14:08.010
So once I got this big
office, and I extended

00:14:08.010 --> 00:14:11.340
for an additional year,
then every single day,

00:14:11.340 --> 00:14:13.380
whether I was delivering
papers or not,

00:14:13.380 --> 00:14:15.630
I was using a similar speech.

00:14:15.630 --> 00:14:17.670
I'd say, hi, my name
is Brian Grazer.

00:14:17.670 --> 00:14:19.560
I work at Warner Bros.
business affairs.

00:14:19.560 --> 00:14:22.170
I kind of fudged
that a little bit.

00:14:22.170 --> 00:14:25.170
And I know everything
about your boss.

00:14:25.170 --> 00:14:27.450
I would love to have a
conversation with them.

00:14:27.450 --> 00:14:29.160
It will last only five minutes.

00:14:29.160 --> 00:14:32.130
And I absolutely
do not want a job.

00:14:32.130 --> 00:14:35.100
So I do that every single
day, so that every single day,

00:14:35.100 --> 00:14:37.830
I could meet someone
that was really

00:14:37.830 --> 00:14:40.200
making a difference in the
entertainment business.

00:14:40.200 --> 00:14:43.400
It could be
television or movies.

00:14:43.400 --> 00:14:45.825
So it wasn't that I counted
on the relationship.

00:14:45.825 --> 00:14:49.320
It was more about a
demystification of how

00:14:49.320 --> 00:14:52.470
this whole system worked.

00:14:52.470 --> 00:14:55.500
Ultimately, what I was able
to learn, even very young,

00:14:55.500 --> 00:14:59.430
was how leverage
got created and used

00:14:59.430 --> 00:15:05.190
as a tool in our in
entertainment business.

00:15:05.190 --> 00:15:09.480
So I kind of stayed, doing that
for about a year and a half.

00:15:09.480 --> 00:15:11.940
And just before I got
the boot, because I

00:15:11.940 --> 00:15:15.750
kept using their Warner
Bros. assets for me,

00:15:15.750 --> 00:15:17.870
I got this one
big meeting with--

00:15:17.870 --> 00:15:20.570
who I really wanted to
meet was Lew Wasserman.

00:15:20.570 --> 00:15:26.110
Lew Wasserman was like the Don
of the modern entertainment

00:15:26.110 --> 00:15:26.610
business.

00:15:26.610 --> 00:15:31.630
The most powerful, mythic man
in the entertainment business,

00:15:31.630 --> 00:15:37.650
he was really the
founder of MCA Universal.

00:15:37.650 --> 00:15:43.920
And literally, everything in
the entertainment business

00:15:43.920 --> 00:15:45.180
revolved around Lew Wasserman.

00:15:45.180 --> 00:15:47.850
So I find a way to
meet Lew Wasserman.

00:15:47.850 --> 00:15:51.510
And I'm already sort
of trying to have

00:15:51.510 --> 00:15:53.337
a conversation with him.

00:15:53.337 --> 00:15:55.170
And he sort of puts his
hands up in the air.

00:15:55.170 --> 00:15:56.503
And he says, just wait a second.

00:15:56.503 --> 00:15:58.181
You're not coming
into my office.

00:15:58.181 --> 00:15:59.680
And I thought, well,
like everybody,

00:15:59.680 --> 00:16:00.846
I was going into his office.

00:16:00.846 --> 00:16:02.130
But no go.

00:16:02.130 --> 00:16:06.550
So he comes back with a
legal tab and a pencil.

00:16:06.550 --> 00:16:08.550
And he said, take these.

00:16:08.550 --> 00:16:09.900
So I take them.

00:16:09.900 --> 00:16:12.660
And he says put the
pencil to the paper,

00:16:12.660 --> 00:16:16.320
and it has greater value than
it did as separate parts.

00:16:16.320 --> 00:16:20.200
Now, get out of here, which
was kind of embarrassing.

00:16:20.200 --> 00:16:23.910
But what I realized was he was
saying that you don't really

00:16:23.910 --> 00:16:26.070
have anything.

00:16:26.070 --> 00:16:30.380
You might have a gift to
get into people's office

00:16:30.380 --> 00:16:32.970
and to turn and
create a conversation,

00:16:32.970 --> 00:16:34.710
but you don't own anything.

00:16:34.710 --> 00:16:36.960
So I realized I better put
the pencil to the paper

00:16:36.960 --> 00:16:38.950
and start writing ideas.

00:16:38.950 --> 00:16:42.930
And I kind of industrialized
the idea of business.

00:16:42.930 --> 00:16:46.080
And I would, every
day, have many ideas

00:16:46.080 --> 00:16:48.030
and send them registered
mail to myself.

00:16:48.030 --> 00:16:50.890
And I ended up with a
box of hundreds of ideas,

00:16:50.890 --> 00:16:53.704
including the one
called Splash--

00:16:53.704 --> 00:16:55.620
that was a man falling
in love with a mermaid,

00:16:55.620 --> 00:16:59.530
starring Tom Hanks--
and many others.

00:16:59.530 --> 00:17:06.839
But I realized that unless you
can codify or write original

00:17:06.839 --> 00:17:09.660
ideas and prove that
they are valuable--

00:17:09.660 --> 00:17:13.020
you have to make them valuable--

00:17:13.020 --> 00:17:14.240
you don't have anything.

00:17:14.240 --> 00:17:17.349
SPEAKER 1: I want to talk about
idea generation for a second.

00:17:17.349 --> 00:17:20.430
I imagine curiosity
conversations probably

00:17:20.430 --> 00:17:21.900
play into different ideas.

00:17:21.900 --> 00:17:23.566
And you've talked
about how they've even

00:17:23.566 --> 00:17:24.869
turned into movies.

00:17:24.869 --> 00:17:26.670
Do you have any other
kind of processes

00:17:26.670 --> 00:17:31.960
to help spur creativity
and come up with ideas?

00:17:31.960 --> 00:17:36.820
BRIAN GRAZER: Do I have other
ways to spur creativity?

00:17:36.820 --> 00:17:39.260
Well, I read.

00:17:39.260 --> 00:17:44.010
But I don't really read fiction.

00:17:44.010 --> 00:17:49.230
I mean, the first 15 years
of my being a producer,

00:17:49.230 --> 00:17:51.060
I just did comedies.

00:17:51.060 --> 00:17:52.890
Comedies are fiction.

00:17:52.890 --> 00:17:54.450
Well, I don't know.

00:17:54.450 --> 00:17:56.730
Whatever you think they are.

00:17:56.730 --> 00:17:58.290
They're kind of a combination.

00:18:01.220 --> 00:18:03.580
I like the curiosity
conversations,

00:18:03.580 --> 00:18:13.580
because I just know that
knowing your inner truth--

00:18:13.580 --> 00:18:16.760
whatever that is-- and really
diagnosing what that is--

00:18:16.760 --> 00:18:18.590
so you're not
bullshitting yourself--

00:18:18.590 --> 00:18:23.300
I know the inner truth that once
you start to understand that

00:18:23.300 --> 00:18:29.810
and it's schematic, that
is a way to build ideas.

00:18:29.810 --> 00:18:33.140
The movie "Friday Night
Lights" was about me.

00:18:33.140 --> 00:18:35.150
It was really just
because I got cut

00:18:35.150 --> 00:18:38.140
in a very humiliating way
from high school football,

00:18:38.140 --> 00:18:39.110
from Coach Ogawa.

00:18:39.110 --> 00:18:41.660
He cut me in front
of like 250 kids.

00:18:41.660 --> 00:18:47.870
And the pain of
that was so awesome.

00:18:47.870 --> 00:18:49.970
I mean, it was so
memorable to me

00:18:49.970 --> 00:18:54.490
that I was able to sort of
think it through and go--

00:18:54.490 --> 00:18:57.549
when he pointed to Richard
Cox, over there, and he said

00:18:57.549 --> 00:18:58.340
he was quarterback.

00:18:58.340 --> 00:19:00.423
And he said to Perry
Shellmyer, you're nose guard.

00:19:00.423 --> 00:19:03.800
And he said to Brian
Grazer, your status?

00:19:03.800 --> 00:19:05.330
And I said, tailback.

00:19:05.330 --> 00:19:06.330
He said, incorrect.

00:19:06.330 --> 00:19:07.570
Cut.

00:19:07.570 --> 00:19:10.310
I was no longer a human
being in that moment.

00:19:10.310 --> 00:19:15.126
And I was able to
sort of catalog that

00:19:15.126 --> 00:19:16.250
and many other experiences.

00:19:16.250 --> 00:19:19.730
But that one in
particular, I realized

00:19:19.730 --> 00:19:24.340
that that lived inside this book
called "Friday Night Lights."

00:19:24.340 --> 00:19:28.000
Because anything you read
has multiple interpretations,

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:29.326
right?

00:19:29.326 --> 00:19:31.950
SPEAKER 1: I want to skip ahead,
chronologically, a little bit.

00:19:31.950 --> 00:19:34.540
You're in the '80s.

00:19:34.540 --> 00:19:36.460
You're working at Paramount.

00:19:36.460 --> 00:19:39.509
And you want to meet Ron Howard.

00:19:39.509 --> 00:19:41.050
He had done "The
Andy Griffith Show."

00:19:41.050 --> 00:19:42.130
He'd done "Happy Days."

00:19:45.121 --> 00:19:47.620
It almost seems like you knew
you wanted to partner with him

00:19:47.620 --> 00:19:50.080
before you met him.

00:19:50.080 --> 00:19:52.810
What about him made you
say, this is the guy.

00:19:52.810 --> 00:19:56.545
This is the guy I want to work
with for the rest of my life.

00:19:56.545 --> 00:19:57.970
BRIAN GRAZER: Well, I didn't.

00:19:57.970 --> 00:19:59.500
I actually didn't know.

00:19:59.500 --> 00:20:03.430
I just had this quota of
meeting a new person every day.

00:20:03.430 --> 00:20:06.640
So I saw Ron Howard
out of my office.

00:20:06.640 --> 00:20:08.560
And I yelled out
at him like, hey!

00:20:08.560 --> 00:20:10.360
You know, like that.

00:20:10.360 --> 00:20:11.590
And he didn't know who I was.

00:20:11.590 --> 00:20:12.460
And I scared him.

00:20:14.894 --> 00:20:17.310
Then I called his office and
said, I got to meet with you.

00:20:17.310 --> 00:20:18.220
I found a way.

00:20:18.220 --> 00:20:21.040
Because you can get in,
if you really work at it.

00:20:21.040 --> 00:20:23.860
If you're resourceful,
and polite,

00:20:23.860 --> 00:20:27.650
you can get people
to meet with you.

00:20:27.650 --> 00:20:29.640
But then, when he
walked into my office,

00:20:29.640 --> 00:20:32.150
he had this sort of
aura of goodness.

00:20:32.150 --> 00:20:36.350
Or it was perceptible to
me that, energetically, he

00:20:36.350 --> 00:20:40.110
had goodness about him.

00:20:40.110 --> 00:20:43.170
I'm sure you guys feel
stuff like that, right?

00:20:43.170 --> 00:20:47.100
You know, you feel like
that person's a bad vibe.

00:20:47.100 --> 00:20:50.120
I don't think I want
to be around that.

00:20:50.120 --> 00:20:52.650
So it's a very
important metric to me,

00:20:52.650 --> 00:20:56.790
how I feel, energetically,
towards somebody.

00:20:56.790 --> 00:20:59.780
Because I can think about it.

00:20:59.780 --> 00:21:03.800
You feel it, that truth,
and then I often just

00:21:03.800 --> 00:21:05.950
think, how will this end?

00:21:05.950 --> 00:21:10.170
And if you build
that out, and you

00:21:10.170 --> 00:21:14.715
feel like, I think this will end
bad, then you shouldn't start.

00:21:14.715 --> 00:21:21.210
But with Ron, I felt like he
just had this aura of goodness

00:21:21.210 --> 00:21:23.250
about him.

00:21:23.250 --> 00:21:25.530
It was kind of biblical for me.

00:21:25.530 --> 00:21:28.140
Of course, I was looking
for that, probably.

00:21:28.140 --> 00:21:30.210
I didn't know he
could actually direct.

00:21:30.210 --> 00:21:32.100
I had no idea he could direct.

00:21:32.100 --> 00:21:34.380
I just liked him
and thought I should

00:21:34.380 --> 00:21:37.425
support a guy that seemed good.

00:21:37.425 --> 00:21:39.030
SPEAKER 1: Seemed
like it worked out.

00:21:39.030 --> 00:21:39.905
BRIAN GRAZER: It did.

00:21:39.905 --> 00:21:42.355
It worked out.

00:21:42.355 --> 00:21:45.210
SPEAKER 1: Can you
give us a story

00:21:45.210 --> 00:21:48.480
of the making of a movie that
seemed very unlikely that it

00:21:48.480 --> 00:21:51.650
would be made at the start,
and you kind of willed it

00:21:51.650 --> 00:21:54.409
into fruition?

00:21:54.409 --> 00:21:55.950
BRIAN GRAZER: I've
had a lot of them.

00:21:55.950 --> 00:21:58.110
The first one was "Splash."

00:21:58.110 --> 00:22:02.400
Because I had hundreds of
rejections over the course of

00:22:02.400 --> 00:22:04.120
like five years.

00:22:04.120 --> 00:22:07.350
Just every person
rejected it, repeatedly--

00:22:07.350 --> 00:22:11.070
every studio, every buyer--

00:22:11.070 --> 00:22:20.630
which caused me to get tough
and become durable, that way.

00:22:20.630 --> 00:22:27.834
And I think what I
learned was "Splash,"

00:22:27.834 --> 00:22:29.500
even though it was a
man falling in love

00:22:29.500 --> 00:22:35.260
with a mermaid, its inner
theme, its interior theme

00:22:35.260 --> 00:22:36.820
was about love.

00:22:36.820 --> 00:22:40.630
And I realized in retrospect
that people, through the script

00:22:40.630 --> 00:22:44.920
or through my pitch,
couldn't see that.

00:22:44.920 --> 00:22:46.780
Or they just didn't like it.

00:22:46.780 --> 00:22:47.470
I don't know.

00:22:47.470 --> 00:22:51.290
But I think if you
can pitch a theme--

00:22:51.290 --> 00:22:55.360
if you have a story, but
you know the interior theme,

00:22:55.360 --> 00:22:59.080
and you case build
to sell your theme,

00:22:59.080 --> 00:23:01.690
themes are often irrefutable.

00:23:04.920 --> 00:23:06.337
But I just didn't
know that, then.

00:23:06.337 --> 00:23:08.211
So I had hundreds and
hundreds of rejections.

00:23:08.211 --> 00:23:09.260
I finally got it made.

00:23:09.260 --> 00:23:10.390
It was brutal.

00:23:13.120 --> 00:23:17.770
And then, the movie that
models this best for me

00:23:17.770 --> 00:23:19.614
was this movie called
"American Gangster."

00:23:19.614 --> 00:23:21.030
I don't know if
you ever saw that,

00:23:21.030 --> 00:23:22.970
with Russell Crowe
and Denzel Washington.

00:23:22.970 --> 00:23:29.890
But it was many, many
years later after splash.

00:23:29.890 --> 00:23:31.900
And the studio decided
they were going

00:23:31.900 --> 00:23:36.250
to fire the director,
just months before we

00:23:36.250 --> 00:23:37.720
were starting to shoot.

00:23:37.720 --> 00:23:40.060
And we already had Russell
Crowe in the movie.

00:23:40.060 --> 00:23:42.010
Sorry, Denzel
Washington in the movie.

00:23:42.010 --> 00:23:43.720
We didn't have Russell Crowe.

00:23:43.720 --> 00:23:44.470
We had a director.

00:23:44.470 --> 00:23:47.050
We'd already spent $32 million.

00:23:47.050 --> 00:23:50.950
But they just felt like
this director scares them.

00:23:50.950 --> 00:23:52.435
They've thought about it a lot.

00:23:52.435 --> 00:23:54.740
He scares them.

00:23:54.740 --> 00:23:56.770
It's going to be a bigger
loss if they actually

00:23:56.770 --> 00:23:57.580
make the movie.

00:23:57.580 --> 00:23:59.890
They'd rather just
write down $32 million.

00:23:59.890 --> 00:24:03.447
And that's really
a lot of money.

00:24:03.447 --> 00:24:04.780
Even today, it's a lot of money.

00:24:04.780 --> 00:24:06.400
But then, it was crazy.

00:24:06.400 --> 00:24:10.070
That was like 12 years ago.

00:24:10.070 --> 00:24:12.950
That's how scared
they were of this guy.

00:24:12.950 --> 00:24:16.630
And anyways, I was able to
immediately recontextualize

00:24:16.630 --> 00:24:20.200
it and get better actors
and a much better director.

00:24:20.200 --> 00:24:26.130
So I forced them, after
they took the write down,

00:24:26.130 --> 00:24:30.060
to talk to me again about
"American Gangster," which

00:24:30.060 --> 00:24:31.330
they didn't want to do.

00:24:31.330 --> 00:24:32.871
They said, we'll
take the write down,

00:24:32.871 --> 00:24:36.850
but don't ever say American
or gangster to us, ever again.

00:24:36.850 --> 00:24:40.787
SPEAKER 1: I love the story
of how you got "8 Mile" made.

00:24:40.787 --> 00:24:42.370
Can you talk about
that a little bit--

00:24:42.370 --> 00:24:47.520
how you met Eminem and slowly
convinced him to do it?

00:24:50.600 --> 00:24:51.735
BRIAN GRAZER: Well, yeah.

00:24:55.260 --> 00:24:59.940
Very quickly, you said,
how do I get ideas?

00:24:59.940 --> 00:25:02.172
I get ideas just by--

00:25:02.172 --> 00:25:04.710
it sounds so simple--

00:25:04.710 --> 00:25:08.040
trying to be as
present as possible.

00:25:08.040 --> 00:25:10.980
So I happened to be in
a taxicab in New York.

00:25:10.980 --> 00:25:13.080
And as the guy's weaving
around and everything,

00:25:13.080 --> 00:25:17.640
I'm listening to this
faint conversation going on

00:25:17.640 --> 00:25:20.260
in the taxicab, on the radio--

00:25:20.260 --> 00:25:24.000
a local Manhattan radio.

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:28.620
And ODB, Old Dirty Bastard,
is being interviewed

00:25:28.620 --> 00:25:30.360
by some talk show guy.

00:25:30.360 --> 00:25:32.090
And you can't even
understand him.

00:25:32.090 --> 00:25:33.930
He barely makes any sense.

00:25:33.930 --> 00:25:35.990
It's just hard to
really understand him.

00:25:35.990 --> 00:25:38.430
But I thought,
what kind of a guy

00:25:38.430 --> 00:25:41.700
wants to be called
Old Dirty Bastard?

00:25:41.700 --> 00:25:43.680
I mean, that was his
choice to be called that.

00:25:43.680 --> 00:25:47.680
I thought, that's an
interesting choice.

00:25:47.680 --> 00:25:50.460
So I think, I better
go meet this ODB.

00:25:50.460 --> 00:25:53.160
So this is like 25
or 23 years ago.

00:25:53.160 --> 00:25:57.660
So I go meet ODB,
and he was a trip.

00:25:57.660 --> 00:25:59.310
He wouldn't let me
into his studio.

00:25:59.310 --> 00:26:01.495
And everything was a
cost a la carte thing.

00:26:01.495 --> 00:26:03.870
If you want to go in the
studio, it's going to cost this.

00:26:03.870 --> 00:26:05.290
If you want to do that--

00:26:05.290 --> 00:26:06.240
so I just think, wow.

00:26:06.240 --> 00:26:07.740
This guy's so interesting.

00:26:07.740 --> 00:26:12.840
He's funny and also kind
of scary at the same time.

00:26:12.840 --> 00:26:14.790
So after I met
ODB, then I thought

00:26:14.790 --> 00:26:16.510
I'd meet this character,
Slick Rick, that

00:26:16.510 --> 00:26:17.990
wears a patch on his eye.

00:26:17.990 --> 00:26:19.060
He's a rapper.

00:26:19.060 --> 00:26:22.020
He's really kind of a
comical British dude.

00:26:22.020 --> 00:26:23.880
And then I go through
the series of Chuck D,

00:26:23.880 --> 00:26:25.090
et cetera, et cetera.

00:26:25.090 --> 00:26:27.048
And I'm thinking, wow,
this is like a movement.

00:26:29.340 --> 00:26:31.950
East Coast hip hop
is like a movement.

00:26:31.950 --> 00:26:32.880
It can be funny.

00:26:32.880 --> 00:26:35.100
It could be the voice
of the inner city.

00:26:35.100 --> 00:26:36.780
It's a lot of things.

