that you have faith
will someday connect.

00:38:50.630 --> 00:38:51.820
And they do.

00:38:51.820 --> 00:38:54.752
So I forgot the question.

00:38:54.752 --> 00:38:56.210
SPEAKER 1: I think
you answered it.

00:38:56.210 --> 00:38:57.162
BRIAN GRAZER: Did I?

00:38:57.162 --> 00:38:59.542
OK.

00:38:59.542 --> 00:39:02.930
SPEAKER 1: I want to get to the
audience Q&amp;A. But real quick,

00:39:02.930 --> 00:39:04.940
you know Hollywood
is changing so much.

00:39:04.940 --> 00:39:09.170
And Google probably has a
hand in changing it, just

00:39:09.170 --> 00:39:11.790
in terms of content
distribution.

00:39:11.790 --> 00:39:13.640
What do you see
Hollywood looking

00:39:13.640 --> 00:39:17.726
like in the next 30, 40 years?

00:39:17.726 --> 00:39:19.200
BRIAN GRAZER: 30 or 40?

00:39:19.200 --> 00:39:21.440
SPEAKER 1: Yeah, or
whatever time scale

00:39:21.440 --> 00:39:23.345
you think you can tell me about.

00:39:23.345 --> 00:39:24.470
BRIAN GRAZER: I don't know.

00:39:24.470 --> 00:39:32.160
Probably every artist that
can create a sustainable story

00:39:32.160 --> 00:39:34.760
will be their own platform.

00:39:34.760 --> 00:39:37.260
There'll be consolidation
of platforms.

00:39:37.260 --> 00:39:41.690
But probably in the
future of 10 years,

00:39:41.690 --> 00:39:45.486
more artists will have more
power over their own life.

00:39:45.486 --> 00:39:46.690
SPEAKER 1: Got you.

00:39:46.690 --> 00:39:47.190
Cool.

00:39:47.190 --> 00:39:47.976
Does anyone--

00:39:47.976 --> 00:39:50.436
BRIAN GRAZER: I don't
know-- positive.

00:39:50.436 --> 00:39:53.020
SPEAKER 1: Does anybody have
questions, from the audience?

00:39:53.020 --> 00:39:54.771
AUDIENCE: Thanks, I've
really appreciated

00:39:54.771 --> 00:39:56.020
everything you've said so far.

00:39:56.020 --> 00:39:58.797
So I worked in
film for 10 years.

00:39:58.797 --> 00:40:01.130
And a lot of my friends are
aspiring writers, producers,

00:40:01.130 --> 00:40:02.260
and actors.

00:40:02.260 --> 00:40:05.080
I always think the ones who are
aspiring producers-- it just

00:40:05.080 --> 00:40:08.200
seems like the most impossible
business to get into.

00:40:08.200 --> 00:40:12.162
What advice would you have
for aspiring producers?

00:40:12.162 --> 00:40:15.220
BRIAN GRAZER: Well, I'd probably
go back to having an idea.

00:40:15.220 --> 00:40:21.700
Having some IP, whether it's
your own self-generated idea

00:40:21.700 --> 00:40:25.560
or just any IP-- it
could be a short story.

00:40:25.560 --> 00:40:29.030
It could be anything-- you have
to have something if you're

00:40:29.030 --> 00:40:31.204
going to be a producer.

00:40:31.204 --> 00:40:32.870
The definition of a
producer is somebody

00:40:32.870 --> 00:40:36.500
that can generate
an idea, that can

00:40:36.500 --> 00:40:39.440
see the vertical
line of the most

00:40:39.440 --> 00:40:46.670
nascent stage of that idea,
until its final evolution

00:40:46.670 --> 00:40:48.020
or conclusion.

00:40:48.020 --> 00:40:51.140
So you have to be creatively
responsible and fiscally

00:40:51.140 --> 00:40:52.040
responsible.

00:40:52.040 --> 00:40:55.400
So that starting point
to its end vision

00:40:55.400 --> 00:40:59.810
has to have a corresponding
part, financially.

00:40:59.810 --> 00:41:03.500
Both things will change all
of the time, all of the--

00:41:03.500 --> 00:41:06.220
but as I say this, it's
so much like a startup.

00:41:06.220 --> 00:41:07.730
Isn't it?

00:41:07.730 --> 00:41:10.510
Because you start off.

00:41:10.510 --> 00:41:13.310
You're making a movie.

00:41:13.310 --> 00:41:15.740
Let's say the good news
is you have this idea.

00:41:15.740 --> 00:41:17.510
The studio wants to make it.

00:41:17.510 --> 00:41:20.720
You go through this long process
of developing it, da da da da.

00:41:20.720 --> 00:41:22.700
They're for sure going.

00:41:22.700 --> 00:41:25.160
Cost is $50 million.

00:41:25.160 --> 00:41:26.800
And then they go,
we're making it.

00:41:26.800 --> 00:41:27.350
You're in.

00:41:27.350 --> 00:41:29.000
And you feel like, wow, great.

00:41:29.000 --> 00:41:31.520
They go, but we're
making it $30 million.

00:41:31.520 --> 00:41:33.050
Then you have to
figure that out.

00:41:33.050 --> 00:41:34.500
You have to cut scenes out.

00:41:34.500 --> 00:41:36.200
You have to collapse the story.

00:41:36.200 --> 00:41:38.600
Or you have to
convince them it's 40.

00:41:38.600 --> 00:41:42.080
You know, it's multiple
different possibilities.

00:41:42.080 --> 00:41:44.570
But you have to start
owning something.

00:41:44.570 --> 00:41:47.450
AUDIENCE: So it seems
that, to me, you

00:41:47.450 --> 00:41:52.160
said presence is kind of
the core of how you maintain

00:41:52.160 --> 00:41:54.230
and grow your curiosity.

00:41:54.230 --> 00:41:58.430
And I'm just curious about how
you use personal technology

00:41:58.430 --> 00:41:59.510
in your life?

00:41:59.510 --> 00:42:01.410
And I can see that
going in two ways.

00:42:01.410 --> 00:42:04.520
One is a distraction,
but one is an enhancement

00:42:04.520 --> 00:42:05.870
to your curiosity.

00:42:05.870 --> 00:42:08.120
And how you kind of
control your behavior,

00:42:08.120 --> 00:42:10.610
when it comes to personal
technology, what you use,

00:42:10.610 --> 00:42:11.890
how much time you spend
in the offline world

00:42:11.890 --> 00:42:13.090
versus the online world--

00:42:13.090 --> 00:42:16.760
I'd just love to get
more context around what

00:42:16.760 --> 00:42:17.905
that means in your life.

00:42:17.905 --> 00:42:21.410
BRIAN GRAZER: Well, I
definitely use technology a lot.

00:42:21.410 --> 00:42:29.210
And every day, I'm
doing some search binge.

00:42:29.210 --> 00:42:32.060
Because it's fun for me.

00:42:32.060 --> 00:42:35.120
But I have to start
with some idea.

00:42:35.120 --> 00:42:38.330
And I also paint.

00:42:38.330 --> 00:42:42.020
And I've painted for
about 20 years or so.

00:42:42.020 --> 00:42:45.770
Starting is the hardest
thing, touching the canvas.

00:42:45.770 --> 00:42:48.260
Whether it's an idea to
become a movie or television

00:42:48.260 --> 00:42:54.110
show or a painting, for
me, Brian, knowing myself,

00:42:54.110 --> 00:42:57.350
I can't execute perfection.

00:42:57.350 --> 00:43:02.060
I don't approach anything
knowing Brian Grazer is

00:43:02.060 --> 00:43:06.440
going to execute to perfection.

00:43:06.440 --> 00:43:12.490
I try to have originality
as a differentiator.

00:43:12.490 --> 00:43:19.140
So the original idea
is the one that I

00:43:19.140 --> 00:43:21.450
will put the highest value on.

00:43:21.450 --> 00:43:27.540
And it's the original idea that
that stress test is the one

00:43:27.540 --> 00:43:30.880
that I'm interested in.

00:43:30.880 --> 00:43:35.810
To be the greatest artisan is
just not interesting to me.

00:43:35.810 --> 00:43:38.270
And I don't think I
could succeed at it.

00:43:38.270 --> 00:43:41.750
But I think I can
have original ideas.

00:43:41.750 --> 00:43:47.150
And like now, there's a lot
of evidence that proves that.

00:43:47.150 --> 00:43:50.210
But that's where I put my value.

00:43:50.210 --> 00:43:54.210
And then of course, I will
employ, through collaboration,

00:43:54.210 --> 00:43:58.430
the ability to execute it to
the highest quality possible.

00:43:58.430 --> 00:44:03.130
But I don't start like Chris
Nolan, who did "Dunkirk."

00:44:03.130 --> 00:44:06.050
I don't start going, I
know I can execute this

00:44:06.050 --> 00:44:10.910
to a level 100.

00:44:10.910 --> 00:44:12.530
If I were to compare
to any artist--

00:44:12.530 --> 00:44:15.440
I'm not this person, because
I'm not as great as this person,

00:44:15.440 --> 00:44:19.900
but Andy Warhol just
did original shit.

00:44:19.900 --> 00:44:21.980
That was it.

00:44:21.980 --> 00:44:26.510
He wasn't like Gerhard
Richter, a scientist of art.

00:44:26.510 --> 00:44:28.920
So that's how I look at it.

00:44:28.920 --> 00:44:33.500
So I use your
Google all the time

00:44:33.500 --> 00:44:38.360
to enrich original
ideas that I feel

00:44:38.360 --> 00:44:43.750
like I'm touching, creating,
or being part of its creation.

00:44:43.750 --> 00:44:45.030
So yeah.

00:44:45.030 --> 00:44:46.120
It's an informant.

00:44:46.120 --> 00:44:47.887
It informs all of that.

00:44:47.887 --> 00:44:48.720
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:44:48.720 --> 00:44:49.600
BRIAN GRAZER: Sure.

00:44:49.600 --> 00:44:52.000
AUDIENCE: Do you have a
process for these curiosity

00:44:52.000 --> 00:44:54.760
conversations, or a standard
set of questions you ask,

00:44:54.760 --> 00:44:57.110
or research you do
before going into them?

00:44:57.110 --> 00:44:59.830
Because it's a skill and
an art to kind of extract

00:44:59.830 --> 00:45:01.790
great stories from
people, as well.

00:45:01.790 --> 00:45:04.030
So how do you go into
these conversations?

00:45:04.030 --> 00:45:07.320
BRIAN GRAZER: You have
to get to the place.

00:45:07.320 --> 00:45:09.370
Like get in flow, right?

00:45:09.370 --> 00:45:16.710
Or in the zone, where you're
hoping for the very best date

00:45:16.710 --> 00:45:19.410
of your lifetime.

00:45:19.410 --> 00:45:22.800
And if you think about
your very best date,

00:45:22.800 --> 00:45:26.220
you weren't constructing
stuff as it's going.

00:45:26.220 --> 00:45:29.535
You're not thinking of what
are you going to say next.

00:45:32.300 --> 00:45:34.020
You're really in
a state of flow,

00:45:34.020 --> 00:45:36.210
and you're so present
that everything

00:45:36.210 --> 00:45:42.210
is evolving in the most
sincere and authentic way.

00:45:42.210 --> 00:45:47.310
I think just being as sincere
as possible, you can be funny.

00:45:47.310 --> 00:45:49.440
And you can goof up,
like I do all the time.

00:45:49.440 --> 00:45:56.080
But I think people feel
when other people are

00:45:56.080 --> 00:45:59.680
a facsimile of authenticity.

00:45:59.680 --> 00:46:01.970
There's a lot of agents
that I deal with,

00:46:01.970 --> 00:46:03.520
I just feel like they're bots.

00:46:03.520 --> 00:46:04.540
You know?

00:46:04.540 --> 00:46:06.190
They go, hey, so
what's going on?

00:46:06.190 --> 00:46:08.470
They come up with questions.

00:46:08.470 --> 00:46:11.620
They somehow learned that
that was a method that

00:46:11.620 --> 00:46:12.760
would create intimacy.

00:46:12.760 --> 00:46:15.304
And I just don't
feel like it does.

00:46:15.304 --> 00:46:15.970
Are you smiling?

00:46:15.970 --> 00:46:17.350
Because it's true, right?

00:46:17.350 --> 00:46:22.210
When you try to
methodologize it--

00:46:22.210 --> 00:46:25.240
AUDIENCE: For me, as I
spoke to you earlier,

00:46:25.240 --> 00:46:26.710
I've had some ideas.

00:46:26.710 --> 00:46:28.540
And they're written down.

00:46:28.540 --> 00:46:31.450
And they're not just ideas, but
the actual scripts are done.

00:46:31.450 --> 00:46:37.080
What's the best way, or a
way, that you would recommend

00:46:37.080 --> 00:46:39.190
getting them produced?

00:46:39.190 --> 00:46:40.232
Like getting them done?

00:46:40.232 --> 00:46:40.940
BRIAN GRAZER: OK.

00:46:40.940 --> 00:46:41.900
This will be horrible.

00:46:41.900 --> 00:46:44.230
What do you think?

00:46:44.230 --> 00:46:46.945
Just take a guess, even
if it's the wrong guess.

00:46:46.945 --> 00:46:47.570
AUDIENCE: Sure.

00:46:47.570 --> 00:46:50.660
For me, like, submitting
to friends in the industry

00:46:50.660 --> 00:46:55.700
that are producers, themselves,
or agents, managers.

00:46:55.700 --> 00:46:58.045
I submit to contests
and stuff like that.

00:46:58.045 --> 00:46:59.750
BRIAN GRAZER: OK, good.

00:46:59.750 --> 00:47:01.370
But I'd augment that.

00:47:01.370 --> 00:47:04.040
People don't really want
to drudge through shit.

00:47:04.040 --> 00:47:09.810
So I think the best way, if that
would be the mechanics for you,

00:47:09.810 --> 00:47:12.950
then you should know how to
say it in a really sexy way,

00:47:12.950 --> 00:47:14.936
in like under a minute.

00:47:14.936 --> 00:47:15.650
AUDIENCE: Got it.

00:47:15.650 --> 00:47:16.700
Working on the pitch.

00:47:16.700 --> 00:47:17.824
Is that what you're saying?

00:47:17.824 --> 00:47:22.940
BRIAN GRAZER: Yeah, but work
on the sexiest, hookiest--

00:47:22.940 --> 00:47:25.940
it could be 30 seconds, but
it forces the person you're

00:47:25.940 --> 00:47:27.500
talking to to ask questions.

00:47:27.500 --> 00:47:28.306
AUDIENCE: Got it.

00:47:28.306 --> 00:47:30.200
BRIAN GRAZER:
People love to talk.

00:47:30.200 --> 00:47:33.180
But they only like to talk if
they think you're interesting.

00:47:33.180 --> 00:47:36.270
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:47:36.270 --> 00:47:37.430
SPEAKER 1: Next question.

00:47:40.160 --> 00:47:42.490
AUDIENCE: So along the
lines of that advice,

00:47:42.490 --> 00:47:45.952
can you give the audience an
example of your sexiest pitch

00:47:45.952 --> 00:47:46.660
that you've done?

00:47:46.660 --> 00:47:49.270
SPEAKER 1: I was just
going to ask that.

00:47:49.270 --> 00:47:51.130
BRIAN GRAZER:
Basically, my career

00:47:51.130 --> 00:47:54.370
began while I was the law clerk.

00:47:54.370 --> 00:47:57.880
And after Lew Wasserman
said, you better have ideas,

00:47:57.880 --> 00:48:02.320
there was this book-- this
Leonard Maltin's "10,000 Titles

00:48:02.320 --> 00:48:04.390
Of Movies Or TV."

00:48:04.390 --> 00:48:05.980
And I realized,
for me, everything

00:48:05.980 --> 00:48:08.950
started with a title or a word.

00:48:08.950 --> 00:48:11.590
And there are certain words
that really wake you up,

00:48:11.590 --> 00:48:12.250
like revenge.

00:48:17.890 --> 00:48:22.660
There are certain words that are
like accelerators that wake you

00:48:22.660 --> 00:48:24.640
up, and they make you
go, what does that mean,

00:48:24.640 --> 00:48:27.910
or that have danger to them.

00:48:27.910 --> 00:48:30.140
So I'd go through this book.

00:48:30.140 --> 00:48:31.030
I'd get these words.

00:48:31.030 --> 00:48:33.520
They then became titles
or the ignition point

00:48:33.520 --> 00:48:35.320
of what my question would be.

00:48:38.626 --> 00:48:39.750
I mean, "A Beautiful Mind."

00:48:39.750 --> 00:48:41.330
I could do any of them.

00:48:41.330 --> 00:48:42.510
You should ask me.

00:48:42.510 --> 00:48:45.170
I can do to any of them.

00:48:45.170 --> 00:48:47.270
I made three movies
all in a year

00:48:47.270 --> 00:48:51.630
that were all because the studio
dared me to make a small budget

00:48:51.630 --> 00:48:52.130
movie.

00:48:52.130 --> 00:48:56.110
So I made the movie "Friday
Night Lights," "Blue Crush--"

00:48:56.110 --> 00:49:01.090
it's like a girl empowerment
movie about three girls at surf

00:49:01.090 --> 00:49:02.690
on the North shore of Oahu--

00:49:02.690 --> 00:49:06.160
and then "8 Mile."

00:49:06.160 --> 00:49:12.710
And they all began
with "did you know?"

00:49:12.710 --> 00:49:15.770
I looked at it like this-- have
you ever watched 60 minutes?

00:49:15.770 --> 00:49:17.950
It's been on for 30 years.

00:49:17.950 --> 00:49:21.250
I thought to myself, if I had
to work for one of those guys,

00:49:21.250 --> 00:49:25.240
like Dan Rather or whatever,
and Dan Rather goes,

00:49:25.240 --> 00:49:29.740
he only has like a minute,
I'm a junior nobody.

00:49:29.740 --> 00:49:32.290
I said to everybody that works
for me, including myself, I

00:49:32.290 --> 00:49:34.930
have to pretend like I'm
working for Dan Rather.

00:49:34.930 --> 00:49:36.910
And I got like
one minute to say,

00:49:36.910 --> 00:49:40.060
did you know that this thing
is going on in central Africa,

00:49:40.060 --> 00:49:41.610
in the Congo right now?

00:49:41.610 --> 00:49:42.970
That duh duh duh.

00:49:42.970 --> 00:49:45.610
You have to talk like that.

00:49:45.610 --> 00:49:47.812
That would be how I do it, OK.

00:49:47.812 --> 00:49:52.186
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
and now into the valley

00:49:52.186 --> 00:49:53.158
of disillusionment.

00:49:53.158 --> 00:49:56.410
Do you think that could be a
medium for storytelling that's

00:49:56.410 --> 00:49:56.930
viable?

00:49:56.930 --> 00:49:58.304
Or do you think
it's best or not?

00:49:58.304 --> 00:50:03.040
BRIAN GRAZER: Well, I liked your
question that's a conclusion.

00:50:03.040 --> 00:50:05.710
I really like it, because
I feel similarly to you.

00:50:05.710 --> 00:50:08.830
And I've sort of
been on the same--

00:50:08.830 --> 00:50:13.660
I met the guy that created
VR, Jared something,

00:50:13.660 --> 00:50:16.470
literally 25 years ago,
in northern California.

00:50:16.470 --> 00:50:21.370
Anyway, I've been to
every one of those places,

00:50:21.370 --> 00:50:22.990
Magic Leap, all that stuff.

00:50:22.990 --> 00:50:26.320
I think it interrupts
emotionality.

00:50:26.320 --> 00:50:35.470
And optimally, anything
that becomes cinematic

00:50:35.470 --> 00:50:38.950
should ignite emotion.

00:50:38.950 --> 00:50:41.410
And when it ignites emotion,
it becomes indelible.

00:50:41.410 --> 00:50:43.930
And then, all of a sudden,
it becomes a memory

00:50:43.930 --> 00:50:44.860
that you care about.

00:50:44.860 --> 00:50:46.030
You care to tell others.

00:50:46.030 --> 00:50:47.980
It affects you.

00:50:47.980 --> 00:50:52.570
I think VR, so far
in my experience,

00:50:52.570 --> 00:50:54.620
interrupts narrative
storytelling,

00:50:54.620 --> 00:50:57.790
which is the map to emotion.

00:50:57.790 --> 00:51:01.900
So I'd like it to
work, but I haven't

00:51:01.900 --> 00:51:04.654
seen it yet work that way.

00:51:04.654 --> 00:51:07.070
AUDIENCE: So I always got the
vibe that in Hollywood there

00:51:07.070 --> 00:51:10.270
were tons of aspiring
actors and actresses

00:51:10.270 --> 00:51:15.380
who are working minimum wage
jobs trying to "make it."

00:51:15.380 --> 00:51:17.860
And probably the same thing
with screenwriters, I always

00:51:17.860 --> 00:51:20.440
see a bunch of them in
Starbucks and so forth.

00:51:20.440 --> 00:51:22.960
Are there any roles
in Hollywood that you

00:51:22.960 --> 00:51:25.490
feel like there's actually
a shortage of people for?

00:51:25.490 --> 00:51:28.390
Like if we had more of
this type of person,

00:51:28.390 --> 00:51:31.080
more overall stuff
would get created.

00:51:31.080 --> 00:51:35.000
BRIAN GRAZER: Anything other
than straight American, there's

00:51:35.000 --> 00:51:35.500
less of.

00:51:35.500 --> 00:51:36.870
There's too little of.

00:51:36.870 --> 00:51:41.180
It And it's weird.

00:51:41.180 --> 00:51:47.200
The movie business, which is
sort of posited or positioned

00:51:47.200 --> 00:51:50.830
to be really liberal, I
found it's not very liberal,

00:51:50.830 --> 00:51:52.150
actually.

00:51:52.150 --> 00:51:53.590
It's very ethnocentric.

00:51:53.590 --> 00:51:55.420
It's very judgmental.

00:51:55.420 --> 00:51:59.230
It's kind of its own
hypocrite, in my opinion.

00:51:59.230 --> 00:52:05.130
It lives in its own hypocrisy,
in that there's usually

